# Salesforce Development Standards

## Governor Limits - Design for Bulk

Salesforce enforces strict limits per transaction. Always bulkify code, absolutely no queries in loops.

## SOQL Best Practices

```apex
// ✅ Only needed fields, filtered, with relationship queries
List<Account> accounts = [
    SELECT Id, Name, (SELECT Id, FirstName FROM Contacts)
    FROM Account
    WHERE Id IN :accountIds
    WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED
];
```

- Always use WHERE clauses and LIMIT when appropriate
- Use `WITH SECURITY_ENFORCED` to respect FLS
- Filter on indexed fields (standard, ExternalId, unique)

## Security - CRUD/FLS Enforcement

**Utility class**: Check for existing `SecurityEnforcer` in project. If none exists, copy from `templates/salesforce/classes/SecurityEnforcer.cls`

```apex
SecurityEnforcer.checkReadable(Account.SObjectType, new List<SObjectField>{Account.Name});
SecurityEnforcer.checkCreatable(Account.SObjectType, new List<SObjectField>{Account.Name});
List<Account> safeRecords = (List<Account>) SecurityEnforcer.stripInaccessible(AccessType.CREATABLE, accounts);
insert safeRecords;
if (SecurityEnforcer.isUpdateable(Account.SObjectType)) { /* update */ }
```

Use `with sharing` by default, `without sharing` only when explicitly necessary.

## Test Classes (85% Coverage Required)

- Write tests alongside code — sandbox deployments enforce the 85% coverage gate
- Use `@TestSetup` for common data, `Test.startTest()/stopTest()` to reset limits
- Test bulk (200+ records), positive, negative, and boundary cases
- Never use `seeAllData=true`; create isolated test data
- Use `UniversalMocker` for mocking dependencies if available (see `references/UniversalMock/`)

## Salesforce Test Data Standard

### Fluent Builders (all profiles)
- One builder per SObject type extending `BaseFluentBuilder` in `testsupport/builders/`
- Valid-by-default with `TestIds.nextSuffix()` for unique values
- NO DML, NO queries in builders

### DML Layer (profile-specific)
- **Lightweight**: `TestDataGraph` — register records, declare relationships, commit once
- **Enterprise**: `Application.UnitOfWork.newInstance()` — same pattern as production code

### Scenario Fixtures
- Name by business state, not object graphs
- Return result objects with all created records and IDs
- Fixtures use the profile's DML layer internally

## Sandbox Deployment Workflow

```bash
sf project retrieve start --metadata ApexClass:MyClass
sf project deploy start --source-dir force-app --dry-run
sf project deploy start --source-dir force-app --test-level RunLocalTests
```

## Creating Custom Objects and Fields

Always create an accompanying permission set and add it to the Admin PSG.

## Async Processing

- **Queueable**: Complex processing, chaining, callouts (prefer over Future)
- **Batch Apex**: Large volumes (thousands to millions of records)
- **Scheduled Apex**: Recurring jobs (thin — just kick off Batch/Queueable)
- **Platform Events**: Event-driven, decoupled publishers/subscribers
- Always implement `Database.AllowsCallouts` for HTTP; never enqueue from loops
- See `references/async-patterns.md` for detailed examples

## Error Handling

Use `Database.insert(records, false)` for partial success and iterate `Database.SaveResult` for errors.

## Logging

Use `System.debug()` with appropriate `LoggingLevel`. See profile-specific rules for enterprise logging options.

## Configuration Strategy

Never hardcode configurable values. Use the right mechanism:
- **Custom Metadata Types**: Admin-managed rules, feature flags, mappings, thresholds (deployable, zero-SOQL via `getAll()`)
- **Custom Labels**: User-facing translatable text (error messages, email subjects, UI text)
- **Custom Settings (Hierarchy)**: Per-user/profile runtime overrides (debug mode, bypass flags)
- **Custom Objects**: End-user-managed data needing full CRUD UI (pricing, routing rules)

Never hardcode: URLs, endpoints, thresholds, error messages, picklist values in branching logic.
See profile-specific rules for configuration access patterns.

## AI Agent Reminders

1. Never hardcode Salesforce IDs
2. Check for existing patterns in project and `references/`
3. Respect naming conventions
4. Avoid SOQL in loops
5. Create meta.xml files for every class/trigger
6. Use Database methods for partial success
7. Test data isolation - never rely on org data
8. Retrieve before modify
9. New objects need permission sets
10. Use templates and references before creating from scratch
